(1001, 'KIC', NULL, 'Jim Reid', 'Board Member', 'Living Water International', 'Missions & Relief Org Boards (Beyond Top-3)', 'Houston, Texas', NULL, NULL, 'high', true, 81, NULL, 'Jim Reid is a retired senior vice president at SEFA (a corporate purchasing cooperative) and serves on the board of Living Water International — a Houston-based faith-driven nonprofit founded in 1990 that has drilled over 24,000 water wells in 17 countries across Sub-Saharan Africa, Latin America, and Asia. Living Water mobilizes churches and communities to implement sustainable clean water and sanitation programs, combining physical water access with the Gospel message. Reid brings executive experience in corporate operations and supply chain management to the board''s governance role. He reflects a pattern common in LWI''s board composition: successful Christian business executives who use retirement as an opportunity to invest governance skills in Kingdom-advancing humanitarian work.', 'Contact through Living Water International''s development team rather than directly — Reid has a very low public profile. Call LWI at (713) 237-9901 or email partnerships@water.cc and ask to be connected with board member Jim Reid. A GCU-LWI student mission trip partnership is the right conversation framework — start institutionally before going personal.

Contact: Living Water International: 17220 Katy Freeway, Houston, TX 77094. Phone: (281) 207-7800. Email: info@water.cc. livingwater.net', 'Board member of Living Water International, a Christian clean water ministry serving the poorest globally. Retired SEFA executive who chose post-career service through Christian humanitarian work.', 'No direct GCU connection. Living Water International''s mission of clean water + Gospel witness aligns with GCU''s global outreach programs and nursing/public health curriculum. A GCU student mission trip partnership with LWI would be a natural institutional conversation.', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"date": "Jan 14, 2026", "title": "LWI Leadership Page \u2014 confirms Jim Reid as Retired SVP SEFA, Board Member", "source": "Living Water International", "url": "https://water.cc/leadership/"}, {"date": "2025", "title": "Living Water International GuideStar Profile \u2014 nonprofit financials and board", "source": "GuideStar / Candid", "url": "https://www.guidestar.org/profile/76-0324875"}, {"date": "2025", "title": "Living Water International official website", "source": "water.cc", "url": "https://water.cc/"}]'::jsonb, 'Retired senior VP at SEFA; board member of Living Water International; bridges corporate leadership with global Christian humanitarian service.', 'Dear Mr. Reid,

I''m reaching out from Grand Canyon University — the largest Christian university in America. Living Water International''s mission is one we deeply admire.

Would you be open to a 20-minute call with President Brian Mueller?

With great respect,
[Name] | Grand Canyon University | [Phone]', '["https://water.cc/leadership/", "https://www.guidestar.org/profile/76-0324875", "https://water.cc/"]'::jsonb),
(1002, 'KIC', NULL, 'Dr. Paul Virts', NULL, 'NRB', 'Christian Media & Broadcasting', 'Manassas, Virginia', NULL, NULL, 'high', true, 81, NULL, 'Dr. Paul Virts is a missiologist and researcher who has served in senior roles at the intersection of Christian higher education, global missions research, and evangelical strategy. He has been involved with organizations working to track and advance global Christianity, bringing academic rigor to questions of church growth, unreached peoples, and Great Commission strategy. His work bridging research, missions, and Christian institutional leadership makes him a relevant figure for GCU''s Kingdom Impact Council, particularly as GCU develops its global missions and Christian studies programs.

Other board roles: NRB — National Religious Broadcasters (President). NRB Political Action Committee (oversight). International Christian Media Commission (NRB affiliate).', 'Email NRB directly: info@nrb.org or pvirts@nrb.org (format). Call NRB HQ: (703) 330-7000. NRB''s annual convention (held each spring) is the ideal meeting venue — GCU should have a presence there. This is an institutional partnership conversation — GCU''s College of Arts and Media is the right department to drive this relationship.

Contact: National Religious Broadcasters: 7229 Smith Creek Road, Suite 200, Manassas, VA 20109. Phone: (703) 330-7000. Email: info@nrb.org. President contact: pvirts@nrb.org', 'President of the National Religious Broadcasters, the primary association of Christian media organizations in America. Missiologist who integrates Great Commission research with institutional Christian leadership.', 'NRB''s 200M weekly audience reach is a massive potential platform for GCU. A GCU broadcast media program partnership, speaking slot at NRB''s annual convention, or named GCU scholarship for students pursuing Christian media careers could all result from this relationship. GCU''s growing College of Arts and Media is the natural bridge.', '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, 'Retired broadcast executive with tenure at University of Northwestern and Leading the Way; advises Christian broadcasting industry.', 'Dear Dr. Virts,

I''m reaching out from Grand Canyon University — the largest Christian university in America. NRB''s mission and ours overlap in meaningful ways.

Would you be open to a brief call with President Brian Mueller?

With great respect,
[Name] | Grand Canyon University | [Phone]', '["https://religionnews.com/2020/07/29/major-new-study-on-charitable-giving-offers-reassurance-and-warning-to-faith-based-nonprofits/", "https://nrb.org/who-we-are/leadership/board-of-governors/"]'::jsonb),
(1003, 'KIC', NULL, 'Jim Caldwell', 'Retired NFL Head Coach; Ordained Baptist Minister', 'NFL (Head Coach — Indianapolis Colts, Detroit Lions)', 'Christian Pro Sports Team Owners & GMs', 'Durham, North Carolina', NULL, NULL, 'high', true, 76, NULL, 'James Caldwell (born January 16, 1955, Beloit, Wisconsin) is one of the most accomplished and respected coaches in NFL history. He played four years as a defensive back at the University of Iowa (1973-1976), setting a school record for blocked kicks in a single season. He was the first African-American head football coach in the Atlantic Coast Conference (ACC), serving at Wake Forest University from 1993-2000. He then joined Tony Dungy''s Indianapolis Colts staff as quarterbacks coach (2002-2008), working closely with Peyton Manning at the peak of his career. He became head coach of the Colts in 2009, going 14-2 in his debut season and reaching Super Bowl XLIV. He was offensive coordinator for the Baltimore Ravens when they won Super Bowl XLVII (2013). He served as head coach of the Detroit Lions (2014-2017), compiling a 36-28 record with two playoff appearances — one of the best stretches in franchise history. He most recently served as Senior Advisor/Assistant with the Carolina Panthers (2023-2025), departing in May 2026. He is an ordained Baptist minister who openly shares how Christian faith drives his coaching philosophy of grace, perseverance, and accountability. He is married to Cheryl Caldwell; they have five children and four grandchildren. He grew up in Beloit, Wisconsin, where a gymnasium was named in his honor in 2016.', 'Reach through Tony Dungy — Caldwell''s longtime mentor and fellow Christian NFL leader who has spoken at faith-based universities. Tony Dungy is the single warmest intro path. Alternatively contact through AAE Speakers Bureau (1-800-698-2536) for a speaking engagement inquiry. Caldwell is currently at Stanford as interim coach (2025 season) — Stanford Athletics is another contact point. He responds well to faith-based outreach that honors his ministry calling alongside his coaching career.

Contact: Jim Caldwell does not maintain a public contact page. Reach through NFL coaching alumni networks or Indianapolis Colts/Detroit Lions alumni community. LinkedIn: linkedin.com/in/jimcaldwell', 'Ordained Baptist minister who preaches at churches and shares how Christian faith drives his coaching philosophy of grace and perseverance.', 'GCU''s large athletics program and sports management curriculum are natural fits for Caldwell. Tony Dungy — who mentored Caldwell — has spoken at Christian universities and is part of the same faith-in-sports network. An ordained minister with two Super Bowl rings is an extraordinarily compelling chapel or leadership event speaker.', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"date": "May 18, 2026", "title": "Jim Caldwell no longer on Carolina Panthers staff entering 2026 season", "source": "ClutchPoints", "url": "https://clutchpoints.com/articles/jim-caldwell-no-longer-on-panthers-staff-entering-2026"}, {"date": "May 19, 2026", "title": "Jim Caldwell No Longer On Panthers'' Staff \u2014 departed after serving as Senior Advisor since 2023", "source": "Yardbarker", "url": "https://www.yardbarker.com/nfl/articles/jim_caldwell_no_longer_on_panthers_staff/"}, {"date": "2026", "title": "Jim Caldwell Wikipedia \u2014 born Jan 16, 1955 Beloit WI. NFL head coach Colts, Lions. First Black ACC head coach.", "source": "Wikipedia", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jim_Caldwell_(American_football)"}]'::jsonb, 'NFL head coach turned faith-integration leader; one of the few coaches to openly integrate Christian spiritual formation into an NFL coaching staff culture.', 'Dear Coach Caldwell,

I''m reaching out from Grand Canyon University — the largest Christian university in America. Your career and the faith behind it are deeply admired here.

Would you be open to a brief call with President Brian Mueller?

With great respect,
[Name] | Grand Canyon University | [Phone]', '["https://clutchpoints.com/articles/jim-caldwell-no-longer-on-panthers-staff-entering-2026", "https://www.yardbarker.com/nfl/articles/jim_caldwell_no_longer_on_panthers_staff/", "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jim_Caldwell_(American_football)"]'::jsonb),
(1004, 'KIC', NULL, 'William Barr', 'Former Attorney General', 'U.S. Department of Justice', 'Recent Christian White House Senior Staff (Household)', 'McLean, Virginia', NULL, NULL, 'high', true, 76, NULL, 'William Barr served as the 77th U.S. Attorney General (1991–1993 under President George H.W. Bush) and again as the 85th Attorney General (2019–2021 under President Trump) — one of only two people in history to hold that office twice. He is a devout Roman Catholic and one of America''s foremost champions of religious liberty in government. His October 2019 speech at Notre Dame Law School — arguing that aggressive secularism is destroying America''s moral fabric — went viral and sparked a national debate. He served on the board of the Becket Fund for Religious Liberty for 21 years, the organization behind the Hobby Lobby Supreme Court case. He is the inaugural holder of the St. Thomas More Chair at the Catholic Information Center in Washington D.C. He also served on the Time Warner board (2009–2018). He holds a BA from Columbia and a JD from George Washington University Law School.

Other board roles: Catholic Information Center — D.C. (St. Thomas More Chair, inaugural 2021-present; former board). Becket Fund for Religious Liberty (board, 21 years). Time Warner (board, 2009-2018). DynCorp (board). Torridon Law (of counsel).', 'Contact through the Catholic Information Center (202-783-2062, cicdc.org). CIC hosts Barr''s public lectures — position GCU as a co-sponsor or host of a Barr lecture event in Phoenix or Washington D.C. Alternatively approach through Becket Fund for Religious Liberty (becketlaw.org) where Barr served for 21 years. A letter from GCU President Brian Mueller on university letterhead referencing GCU''s religious liberty case history is the right opening.

Contact: William Barr can be reached through Kirkland and Ellis LLP. Kirkland and Ellis: 1301 Pennsylvania Ave NW, Washington DC 20004. Phone: (202) 389-5000.', 'Devout Catholic who has spoken on religious liberty, stating in 2019 that ''the traditional moral order'' based on Judeo-Christian values is under attack.', 'GCU''s status as a faith-integrated university is directly protected by the religious liberty arguments Barr has championed for 30+ years. The Becket Fund — where Barr served for 21 years — won Burwell v. Hobby Lobby, the case that established the legal framework protecting faith-based institutions like GCU.', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"date": "2026", "title": "William Barr \u2014 St. Thomas More Chair, Catholic Information Center speaker profile", "source": "Catholic Information Center", "url": "https://cicdc.org/speakers/william-p-barr/"}, {"date": "2026", "title": "Becket Fund for Religious Liberty \u2014 where Barr served on board for 21 years", "source": "becketlaw.org", "url": "https://www.becketlaw.org"}, {"date": "2026", "title": "William Barr Wikipedia \u2014 77th and 85th U.S. Attorney General", "source": "Wikipedia", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Barr"}]'::jsonb, '77th U.S. Attorney General; Yale Law graduate; public Catholic who defended religious liberty in federal policy; author of One Damn Thing After Another.', 'Dear Attorney General Barr,

I''m writing from Grand Canyon University in Phoenix — the largest Christian university in America. Your work has directly shaped the legal landscape institutions like ours operate in every day.

Would you be open to a brief call with President Brian Mueller?

With deep respect,
[Name] | Grand Canyon University | [Phone]', '["https://cicdc.org/speakers/william-p-barr/", "https://www.becketlaw.org", "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Barr"]'::jsonb),
(1005, 'KIC', NULL, 'Bart Barber', NULL, 'First Baptist Church of Farmersville', 'Baptist Denomination Leaders (Household)', 'Farmersville, Texas', NULL, NULL, 'high', true, 76, NULL, 'Bart Barber was born in 1970 in Lake City, Arkansas, to Jim and Carolyn Barber — the third of four children. His father was an entrepreneur; his mother a homemaker. He was saved in December 1975, just before his sixth birthday, and baptized at Bethabara Baptist Church near Lake City. He surrendered to pastoral ministry at age 11 at an associational summer camp at Mount Zion Baptist Camp in Walcott, Arkansas. He began pastoring at 17 — assuming the pulpit at New Hope Baptist Church in Black Oak, Arkansas during the summer before his senior year of high school. He is a National Merit Scholar who attended Baylor University on scholarship, then earned an M.Div. and Ph.D. in Church History from Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary in Fort Worth. He has served as Senior Pastor of First Baptist Church in Farmersville, Texas since 1999 — where he also raises cattle on a farm, naming his prize bull ''Bully Graham'' in honor of the late Rev. Billy Graham. He was elected the 63rd President of the Southern Baptist Convention in June 2022 (Anaheim, CA) and reelected in 2023 (New Orleans) — leading the denomination of 14 million members through major reforms on sexual abuse accountability. He was featured on CBS 60 Minutes. He is married to Tracy (Brady) Barber; his wife is active in Southern Baptist Disaster Relief Child Care.', 'Email directly: pastor@fbcfarmersville.com or call First Baptist Farmersville at (972) 784-3288. Barber is accessible — he pastors a small-town Texas church and prides himself on not being an elitist denominational insider. Active on Twitter/X @bartbarber — a public mention or DM works. A letter from GCU President Brian Mueller referencing SBC''s role in GCU''s founding (GCU was founded by Southern Baptists in 1949) is the strongest opening.

Contact: Sagemont Church: 11300 S Sam Houston Pkwy W, Houston, TX 77031. Phone: (281) 481-8770. Email: info@sagemont.com. sagemont.com', '"I am a Southern Baptist because I believe the Bible teaches that Jesus saves sinners by grace alone through faith alone" from his presidential nomination speech', 'Barber''s SBC presidency gives him influence over 47,000+ Southern Baptist churches — many of which actively recruit students to GCU. A formal GCU-SBC student ministry scholarship or a GCU presence at the SBC Annual Meeting would be a strategic door this relationship could open.', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"date": "2025", "title": "Bart Barber official bio \u2014 FBC Farmersville, born Lake City AR, saved age 5, started preaching at 15", "source": "FBC Farmersville", "url": "https://www.fbcfarmersville.com/bart"}, {"date": "Apr 12, 2024", "title": "''A unicorn among SBC presidents'' \u2014 Barber reflects on his two-term legacy", "source": "Baptist News Global", "url": "https://baptistnews.com/article/bart-barber-a-unicorn-among-sbc-presidents-reflects-on-the-state-of-the-sbc-as-his-term-concludes/"}, {"date": "Jun 13, 2023", "title": "Barber reelected SBC President with 68% of vote in New Orleans", "source": "Baptist Press", "url": "https://www.baptistpress.com/resource-library/news/barber-reelected-sbc-president/"}, {"date": "2025", "title": "Bart Barber Wikipedia \u2014 SBC President 2022-2024, pastor Farmersville TX", "source": "Wikipedia", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bart_Barber"}]'::jsonb, 'President of the Southern Baptist Convention; pastor of Sagemont Church Houston; led SBC''s response to abuse reform and theological renewal.', 'Dear Pastor Barber,

I''m reaching out from Grand Canyon University — founded by Southern Baptists in 1949 and now the largest Christian university in America.

Would you be open to a 20-minute call with President Brian Mueller?

With great respect,
[Name] | Grand Canyon University | [Phone]', '["https://www.fbcfarmersville.com/bart", "https://baptistnews.com/article/bart-barber-a-unicorn-among-sbc-presidents-reflects-on-the-state-of-the-sbc-as-his-term-concludes/", "https://www.baptistpress.com/resource-library/news/barber-reelected-sbc-president/", "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bart_Barber"]'::jsonb),
(1006, 'KIC', NULL, 'Jack Graham', 'Pastor of Prestonwood Baptist Church', 'Prestonwood Baptist Church', 'Baptist Denomination Leaders (Household)', 'Plano, Texas', NULL, NULL, 'high', true, 76, NULL, 'Dr. Jack Graham has served as Senior Pastor of Prestonwood Baptist Church in Plano, Texas since 1989, growing it from 8,000 members to over 57,000 members across three campuses — making it one of the largest congregations in America. He also leads PowerPoint Ministries, a national radio and television broadcast ministry reaching millions of viewers and listeners worldwide. He served as President of the Southern Baptist Convention (2002–2004), the largest Protestant denomination in the U.S. with over 14 million members. He served as Honorary Chairman of the National Day of Prayer and was a member of President Trump''s Religious Advisory Council, participating in the National Prayer Service at Washington National Cathedral following the 2017 inauguration. He is a bestselling author of numerous books including ''A Man of God,'' ''Unseen,'' and ''Reignite.'' He and wife Deb have three married children and eight grandchildren. NOTE: Graham was named in the 2022 SBC sexual abuse report regarding handling of a youth minister case in the 1980s — handle engagement with care.

Other board roles: Prestonwood Baptist Church (Senior Pastor, 1989-present). PowerPoint Ministries (founder & president). Southern Baptist Convention (former President, 2002-2004). National Day of Prayer (Honorary Chairman). Trump Religious Advisory Council (member).', 'Call Prestonwood Baptist Church directly at (972) 820-5200 and ask for Dr. Graham''s assistant. Or email pastor@prestonwood.org. Graham is in the same Dallas evangelical network as David Green (Hobby Lobby) — a GCU relationship with Graham could open the entire Dallas evangelical donor network. NOTE: Graham was named in a 2022 SBC sexual abuse report regarding a 1980s youth minister case — handle any public association carefully and consult GCU legal before publicizing this relationship.

Contact: Prestonwood Baptist Church: 6801 W Park Blvd, Plano, TX 75093. Phone: (972) 820-5000. PowerPoint Ministries: powerpoint.org. Email: info@prestonwood.org', 'Hosts *PowerPoint Ministries* radio broadcast preaching biblical inerrancy and leads one of America''s largest churches', 'Jack Graham is in the same tight Dallas evangelical giving and ministry network as David Green (Hobby Lobby) — both are connected to the First Baptist Dallas / Prestonwood Baptist orbit of major Southern Baptist donors and leaders. A warm intro from GCU to Graham could open the door to the broader Dallas evangelical network.', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"date": "Mar 12, 2026", "title": "Jack Graham joins faith advisory council for Sen. John Cornyn''s Texas Senate campaign", "source": "Baptist News Global", "url": "https://baptistnews.com/article/paxtons-pastor-joins-faith-team-for-cornyn/"}, {"date": "Feb 3, 2026", "title": "Dr. Jack Graham \u2014 Official bio, Prestonwood Baptist Church (60,000+ members)", "source": "Prestonwood Baptist Church", "url": "https://prestonwood.org/about/our-staff/dr-jack-graham/"}, {"date": "Mar 11, 2026", "title": "PowerPoint Ministries \u2014 Jack Graham''s official ministry site (113 countries, 77M+ downloads)", "source": "jackgraham.org", "url": "https://jackgraham.org/"}, {"date": "2025", "title": "Jack Graham Wikipedia \u2014 born June 30, 1950, Conway, Arkansas. Former SBC President 2002-2004", "source": "Wikipedia", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jack_Graham_(pastor)"}]'::jsonb, 'Senior pastor of Prestonwood Baptist Church (47,000 members); former SBC president; founder of Jack Graham Ministries and PowerPoint Ministries media outreach.', 'Dear Dr. Graham,

