(1069, 'KIC', NULL, 'Buzz Aldrin', 'NASA Astronaut (Retired)', 'NASA', 'christian_astronauts_aerospace', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'low', true, 0, NULL, 'Buzz Aldrin was the second human to walk on the moon during NASA''s Apollo 11 mission in July 1969, spending over two hours on the lunar surface alongside Neil Armstrong. A decorated military pilot and aerospace engineer, Aldrin flew 66 combat missions in the Korean War before joining NASA. On the lunar surface, Aldrin privately observed Communion — reading from the Gospel of John and taking the bread and wine in a deeply personal act of Christian faith, making it one of the most quietly historic moments of his life. After returning from the moon, Aldrin was open about his struggles with depression and alcoholism and credited his Christian faith as a source of restoration. He remained active as a space exploration advocate until his passing in 2024. His willingness to carry his faith to the moon and back makes him one of the most extraordinary Christian public figures of the 20th century.', 'No outreach possible. Buzz Aldrin passed away January 5, 2024. Remove from active prospect list.', 'Took Communion on the moon, reading John 15:5 and sharing the sacrament privately during Apollo 11 mission in 1969.', NULL, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, 'Second person to walk on the moon during Apollo 11, advancing human space exploration.', NULL, '["https://americanminute.com/blogs/todays-american-minute/the-space-race-manned-space-flight-faith-of-astronauts-jesus-walking-on-the-earth-is-more-important-than-man-walking-on-the-moon-james-irwin-apollo-15-american-minute-with-bill-federer", "https://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/biographies/buzz-aldrin/", "https://buzzaldrin.com/", "https://history.princeton.edu/undergraduate/princeton-historical-review/issue-22-23/his-cosmic-ministry"]'::jsonb),
(1070, 'KIC', NULL, 'Ken Fong', 'Podcast Host, Asian America Podcast', NULL, 'asian_american_christian_household', 'Los Angeles, California', NULL, NULL, 'medium', true, 71, NULL, 'Ken Fong is a pastor, author, and Christian leader in the Asian-American evangelical community who served as Senior Pastor of Evergreen Baptist Church of Los Angeles for over two decades. He is a recognized voice in conversations about racial reconciliation, Asian-American Christian identity, and multi-cultural church leadership. Fong hosted the podcast Asian America: The Ken Fong Podcast and has spoken widely on the intersection of faith, culture, and racial identity within American Christianity. His pastoral leadership in the Asian-American evangelical community and his voice in racial reconciliation conversations make him a relevant figure for GCU''s diverse student population.', 'Veteran Asian-American Christian leader with multi-decade church ministry and ongoing podcast platform

Contact: 📍 MAILING ADDRESS: Evergreen Baptist Church of LA: 1301 Rosemead Blvd, Rosemead, CA 91770 | Phone: (626) 288-4990 | ebcla.org', 'Podcast host, Asian America Podcast; recently retired pastor of Evergreen Baptist Church of Los Angeles', NULL, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, 'Long-term senior pastor at historic Asian-American church and host of Asian America Podcast', NULL, '["https://djchuang.com/list-influential-chinese-american-christian-leaders/", "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jE85DFoBzFQ", "https://asianamericapodcast.com/about/", "https://www.pbssocal.org/local-heroes/meet-local-hero-nominee-ken-fong"]'::jsonb),
(1071, 'KIC', NULL, 'J.D. Greear', 'Senior Pastor of The Summit Church', 'The Summit Church', 'Baptist Denomination Leaders (Household)', 'Durham, North Carolina', NULL, NULL, 'medium', true, 71, NULL, 'Dr. J.D. Greear served as the 62nd President of the Southern Baptist Convention (2018–2021), leading the denomination during one of its most significant periods of reform on racial reconciliation and clergy sexual abuse accountability. He is the Senior Pastor of The Summit Church in Durham, North Carolina — a multi-site congregation of 12,000+ members that ranks among the most influential evangelical churches in America. He holds a PhD from Southeastern Baptist Theological Seminary and a ThM from Trinity Evangelical Divinity School. He studied at the International Mission Board and planted churches internationally before returning to lead The Summit. He is the author of multiple books including ''Stop Asking Jesus Into Your Heart,'' ''Gospel,'' and ''Gaining by Losing.'' He and wife Veronica have four children.', 'Email through The Summit Church: jdgreear@summitchurch.com (format) or call (919) 682-7979. Greear is active on social media and accessible. Lead with GCU''s SBC founding heritage — GCU was founded by Southern Baptists in 1949 in Prescott, Arizona. A GCU chapel engagement or joint student ministry partnership is the right opening ask.

Contact: 📍 MAILING ADDRESS: The Summit Church: 2335 Presidential Drive, Durham, NC 27703 | Phone: (919) 682-7979 | summitchurch.com

