(1959, 'KIC', NULL, 'Ross Douthat', 'Columnist, New York Times', 'New York Times', 'christian_journalism_punditry', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'low', true, 10, NULL, 'Ross Douthat is a conservative opinion columnist for the New York Times and one of the most prominent Catholic voices in mainstream American journalism. He has written a weekly column for the Times since 2009, covering politics, religion, culture, and society from an explicitly Catholic perspective. Douthat is a practicing Catholic who converted from liberal Protestantism and has authored Bad Religion: How We Became a Nation of Heretics, To Change the Church, and The Decadent Society, among others. His willingness to engage Catholic theology and the spiritual dimensions of political and cultural life in the pages of the New York Times — a platform notoriously skeptical of religious viewpoints — makes him a unique and valuable presence in American public discourse. He represents the rare figure who speaks Christian truth to secular power with intellectual credibility and mainstream reach.', 'Household-name cultural critic with sustained influence on Christian thought in mainstream media.', 'Practicing Catholic; New York Times columnist who writes frequently on faith and culture for major mainstream platform', NULL, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, 'New York Times columnist providing prominent Catholic voice in mainstream journalism on faith and culture issues', NULL, '["https://www.ncronline.org/opinion/guest-voices/nyt-columnist-ross-douthat-promotes-value-belief", "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3rYUfDI_D5s", "https://as.virginia.edu/news/faith-family-and-future-nyts-ross-douthat-joins-uva-conversation-religions-role-modern-life", "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=acAAVmtvtpI"]'::jsonb),
(1960, 'KIC', NULL, 'Tish Harrison Warren', 'Columnist and Author', 'New York Times', 'christian_journalism_punditry', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'low', true, 10, NULL, 'Tish Harrison Warren is an Anglican priest, author, and former weekly religion columnist for the New York Times. She is the author of Liturgy of the Ordinary: Sacred Practices in Everyday Life, which won the Christianity Today Book of the Year Award, and Prayer in the Night, which won the Christianity Today Award of Merit. Her New York Times column brought thoughtful Anglican Christian reflection on faith, politics, doubt, and everyday life to one of the world''s most influential secular media platforms. Warren is also a former campus minister with InterVarsity Christian Fellowship and holds a master''s degree in theology from the University of Virginia. Her combination of priestly vocation, literary excellence, seminary formation, and secular media presence makes her a rare and significant voice in contemporary American Christianity.', 'Ordained Christian leader with column in New York Times offering Christian witness to secular audience.', 'Anglican priest publicly testifying to faith''s role in daily life via columns and books like *Prayer in the Night*', NULL, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, 'Pastoral reflections on Christianity in contemporary culture with mainstream media reach.', NULL, '["https://faith.yale.edu/people/tish-harrison-warren", "https://religionnews.com/2026/05/11/spiritually-burned-out-tish-harrison-warren-and-some-ancient-monks-have-advice/", "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tish_Harrison_Warren", "https://truettseminary.baylor.edu/person/tish-harrison-warren"]'::jsonb),
(1961, 'KIC', NULL, 'Jemar Tisby', 'Historian and author', NULL, 'Black Church Leaders & Black Evangelical Voices', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'low', true, 10, NULL, 'Historian and New York Times bestselling author critiquing evangelical history on race. Author of New York Times bestseller The Color of Compromise; public Reformed evangelical testimony through numerous talks and writings. Household-name Black evangelical intellectual with major platform influencing Christian thought on race and history.', 'Household-name Black evangelical intellectual with major platform influencing Christian thought on race and history.', 'Author of New York Times bestseller The Color of Compromise; public Reformed evangelical testimony through numerous talks and writings.', NULL, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, 'Historian and New York Times bestselling author critiquing evangelical history on race.', NULL, '["https://jemartisby.substack.com/p/why-im-still-christian", "https://www.harrywalker.com/speakers/jemar-tisby", "https://jemartisby.com/about/", "https://www.thegospelcoalition.org/profile/jemar-tisby/"]'::jsonb),
(1962, 'KIC', NULL, 'Russell Wilson', 'NFL quarterback', NULL, 'Christian Athletes (Household Names)', 'Denver, Colorado', NULL, NULL, 'low', true, 10, NULL, 'Russell Wilson is an NFL quarterback who played 10 seasons with the Seattle Seahawks (2012–2021), winning Super Bowl XLVIII in 2014, and most recently with the Denver Broncos and Pittsburgh Steelers. He attended NC State and the University of Wisconsin. He is one of the most publicly Christian athletes in professional sports — he regularly leads team Bible studies, speaks at churches and Christian conferences, and openly credits his faith for his resilience. He and wife Ciara are prominent figures in both sports and entertainment. He founded the Why Not You Foundation in 2014, focused on education, health, and inspiring youth to dream big. He has spoken at numerous faith-based events and universities.', 'Contact Why Not You Foundation (whynotyoufoundation.com) for program partnerships. For speaking, contact Washington Speakers Bureau or WME Entertainment. Wilson is very accessible on social media. A GCU chapel address or Why Not You Foundation event on campus would be compelling. His faith and education mission through the Foundation is the strongest hook.

Contact: 📍 MAILING ADDRESS: Why Not You Foundation: 505 Union Station, Suite 200, Seattle, WA 98101 | whynotyoufoundation.com

Why Not You Foundation: whynotyoufoundation.com. Speaking through Washington Speakers Bureau or AAE Speakers Bureau. Ciara/Russell Wilson management through WME Entertainment.', 'Vocal Christian athlete listed among famous evangelical athletes in Christian ministry sources.', 'No direct GCU connection documented. Wilson''s faith and Why Not You Foundation''s education focus align directly with GCU''s mission. His star power would make him one of the most impactful chapel or commencement speakers GCU could host.', '[]'::jsonb, '[{"date": "2026", "title": "Why Not You Foundation \u2014 Russell Wilson''s education, health, and youth empowerment foundation", "source": "whynotyoufoundation.com", "url": "https://whynotyoufoundation.com"}, {"date": "2026", "title": "Russell Wilson Wikipedia \u2014 born Nov 29, 1988 Cincinnati OH. Super Bowl XLVIII champion. Born-again Christian.", "source": "Wikipedia", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russell_Wilson"}]'::jsonb, 'NFL quarterback and Super Bowl champion known for public Christian faith expression.', 'Dear Russell,

I''m reaching out from Grand Canyon University — the largest Christian university in America. Your faith and your impact through Why Not You Foundation are deeply admired here.

Would you be open to a brief call with President Brian Mueller?

With great admiration,
[Name] | Grand Canyon University | [Phone]', '["https://whynotyoufoundation.com", "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russell_Wilson"]'::jsonb),
